03868nam a22006495i 9780823256860DE-B159720200723103303.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200723t20152015nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232568607 a10.1515/97808232568602doi  a(DE-B1597)555329  a(OCoLC)915134731  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aBF475 7aLIT0140002bisacsh04a808.11 aShell, Marc, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTalking the Walk & Walking the Talk :bA Rhetoric of Rhythm /cMarc Shell. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2015] 4cÂ©2015  a1 online resource (224 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aVerbal Arts: Studies in Poetics00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- t1. Starting Out: Prologue and Preamble -- t2. Walking Voices -- t3. Trips of the Tongue in Hamlet (1600) -- t4. Talking Cures -- t5. Walkie Talkies -- t6. Marching and Heiling in The Great Dictator (1940) -- t7. Knock-Kneed and Tongue-Tied in The King's Speech (2010) -- t8. Sign Languages -- t9. Postamble and Epilogue -- tNotes -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book argues that we should regard walking and talking in a single rhythmic vision. In doing so, it contributes to the theory of prosody, our understanding of respiration and looking, and, in sum, to the particular links, across the board, between the human characteristics of bipedal walking and meaningful talk.The author first introduces the philosophical, neurological, anthropological, and aesthetic aspects of the subject in historical perspective, then focuses on rhetoric and introduces a tension between the small and large issues of rhythm. He thereupon turns his attention to the roles of breathing in poetry-as a life-and-death matter, with attention to beats and walking poems. This opens onto technical concepts from the classical traditions of rhetoric and philology.Turning to the relationship between prosody and motion, he considers both animals and human beings as both ostensibly able-bodied creatures and presumptively disabled ones. Finally, he looks at dancing and writing as aspects of walking and talking, with special attention to motion in Arabic and Chinese calligraphy.The final chapters of the book provide a series of interrelated representative case studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Poetry.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP / FUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311071187540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823256860zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823256860423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780823256860.jpg  a978-3-11-071187-5  NYUP / FUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK